  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 11.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Whoever shall alter this word",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Rather, \"this edict.\" To alter the terms of a royal decree would in any country be a heinous offence. In Persia, where the monarch was absolute, and where decrees were regarded as \"altering not\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 6:8, 12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), it was a crime of the deepest dye. Hence the severity of the punishment threatened. The punishment has been explained as crucifixion, impalement, and \"whipping at a post;\" but there seems to be no real doubt that crucifixion is intended. Great criminals were almost always crucified by the Persians (see Brisson, 'De Regno Persarum,' 2. pp. 327-329; and comp. 'Behist. Inscr.,' col. 2. par. 14; col. 3. par. 8). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Let his house be made a dunghill",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Some render \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "be",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " confiscated,\" but wrongly. The best Hebraists agree with our translators. The practice of concluding important documents with maledictions was common to the Persians, with the Assyrians, Babylonians, and others (see 'Records of the Past,' vol. 1. pp. 53, 105, 126; vol. 5. p. 26; vol. 7. pp. 19, 20, 56; vol. 9. pp. 35, 36, 95, 100 107, etc.). ",
        "children": []
      },
